data-category.value: It is called hueheana as well as ti'o'o. It is in this recipient that the healer deposits human fingernails, hair, bones (mostly of fingers), the surgical (bamboo) knife as well as the blood of warriors and specialists (of danse, canoe-building, etc.). data-category.name: Encyclopedic info (E)
data-category.value: Ku‚Äôuhƒì is a headdress which is called a'avehie while it is worn. The headdress is linked to the gods of the natural elements. When a person wears it, it turns into a ku‚Äôuhƒì. It is endowed with mana (supernatural/spiritual powers). Ku‚Äôuhƒì means that the work has been achieved that everything is in a perfect state and the work which has been accomplished is endowed with mana. This headdress is worn by a chief, it portrays the image of a house cover which has a sacred character. In particular along the length of each border side of the headdress there is a band of vertical chevrons alternating in black (plaited coconut fiber) and white (tapa/bark cloth) colour. Ku'u is the fine band seperating the border of chevrons with the feather part in the middle which was sown together with a string of coconut fiber. Inside this ku'u (the green-red feather part) is the mana (or force) of the gods. The line (of the ku'u) on the lower side represents the gods of the mountains, whereas the upper line represents the gods of the sea-region. This headdress was made of the feathers of a bird called "u'u peti". It is a headdress belonging to the chiefs. On the green feathers one also sees a yellow colouring. On the corresponding headdress for the female chiefs/princesses there is much less of a yellow colouring which is called "pa'e ku'a ho veivei". "Ho veivei" refers to the preparation of the dance going from one side to another in the rhythm of the drum which is playing the "kaputu hƒì". In the book of Karl von den Steinen this headdress is called pa'e ku'a without distinguishing the gender of the persons wearing this headdress.

data-category.value: Cette parure se porte sur la t√™te. La ceinture est confectionn√©e √† partir des fibres de coco. Au milieu se trouve une nacre, au milieu de celle-ci des repr√©sentations divines. Au-dessus , une repr√©sentation des yeux du crabe appel√© tike (nom ancien) ou kekeve. Ses yeux sont capables de pivoter sur eux-m√™mes et de voir sur un angle de 180 degr√©s. C‚Äôest la partie arri√®re de la t√™te, ce qui veut dire que la personne est aussi capable de voir derri√®re lui. Les tikis ont √©t√© confectionn√©s dans le balsa (puatea). Pour gagner les comp√©titions, les jeunes gar√ßons (ikoharara) ainsi que les jeunes filles (pa‚Äôakakiko‚Äôei) portent le naohomatatike sur lequel les anciens fixent le pavahina. data-category.name: Encyclopedic info (E)
data-category.value: This object is worn on the head. The belt/headband is fabricated with coconut fibers, in the middle there is a mother-of-pearl element on which can be seen godly/divine representations. The upper part of the mother-of-pearl represent eyes of a crab called "tike" (semi-obsolete name) and in contemporary Marquesan "kekeve". The eyes symbolise that they can turn their view around in a 180 degree angle. The person wearing that headband is suppose to have the same visual ability as the tike crab, i.e. having a complete overview/visual control of the situation. What does "oho" mean? It denotes the back part of the head, so in this context it means that the person (wearing the headband) also has the ability to see behind him. The tikis are made of balsa wood (pu'atea). In order to win competitions, the young men (ikoharara) as well as the young women/girls (pa'akiko'ei) wear the naohomatatike on which the elders additionally attach the "pavahina". The first one says: "hemo mua" (lit. 'let go first'), the second says: "hemo 'ua" )lit. 'let go second') and the third say: "tua to'u" (lit. 'back/spine third').

data-category.name: Encyclopedic info (E)
data-category.value: This object has two names, "u'i po'ofi'ifi'iƒÅ" and "tioho". It is used to remove the intestines of a dead body/deceased before the body is mumified. This object is a new version, the one which was orginally used was smaller. It is inserted/introduced tinto the body through the anus and turned round; the intestines wind around the spiral part, then the stick is slowly withdrawn. What does "tƒ´oho" mean? Oho consists of the syllable "ho". The same term is found in "hohonu" which means "deep" or "in the deepness". There is another term which contains "ho", namely "iho" which means "to descend, downwards". Tƒ´ means "high, above", we find this word in "tiketike" which means "high up, elevated". In connection with the statue it means that it has come up from the deepness of the night (h≈ç) and arrives above (tƒ´), thus it arrives in the light. It realises that it is all naked, it feels ashamed for its' naked body. It decides to wrap itself in bark cloth ('epa). .... It also refers to the arrival of humans to the world, the consciousness of their lives as humans, the death and continuation of their existence via the mumification which this object represents.Oho also means "head" which is high up/above (tƒ´) also being the most sacred part of a human being.
